[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question: [bold]Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the [bold]UK[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Response[bold]: [bold]District heating is not more common within the UK for both historical and
[normal] more recent
[normal] reasons.
[normal] Although
[normal] [bold]district
[normal] heating has enormous 
[normal]economic and 
[normal]te
[normal]chnical potential within the UK, its development within the UK has lagged behind that of Europe. 
[normal]District heating has been deployed within the UK since the 
[normal]1950s;
[normal] however its popularity began to wane due to rapidly rising fuel costs in the aftermath of 
[normal]the 1973 oil crisis particularly as most schemes at the time were oil fired.
[normal] 
[normal]Furthermore the
[normal] availability
[normal] of 
[normal]a 
[normal]relatively cheap
[normal] supply of
[normal] indigenous North Sea 
[normal]gas
[normal], reduced
[normal] the UK’s inclination to focus on increased energy efficiency measures
[normal],
[normal] such as distr
[normal]ict heating
[normal],
[normal] at a time when many European countries with  no such supplies had little
[normal] option but to look at increased energy efficiency
[normal] 
[normal]measures including district heating.
[normal]Additionally the p
[normal]oor manag
[normal]ement
[normal] and low quality of installation
[normal] of the earlier installed district heating schemes made many 
[normal]of them unreliable. In contrast, modern pre-insulated pipes and installation technologies result in networks that are reliable over many decades.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]While there is huge potential for greater deploy
[normal]ment of 
[normal]district heating across the UK the relatively small market means 
[normal]that the market for installers remains small and uncompetitive. Added to this is the very high price of installation which makes it hard for many district heating schemes to be financ
[normal]ially viable.
[normal]A sustainable funding mechanism could accelerate the deployment of district heating, making the market more competitive, reducing costs.
[normal] Sustainable funding mechanisms would also achieve more than previous grant funding programmes which were 
[normal]invariably closed part way through the advertised timetable and which led to feast and famine delivery of networks.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UKDEA believes that
[normal] 
[normal]support could be in the form of a Heat Networks Incentive or a 
[normal]loan
[normal] or grant
[normal] mechanism to accelerate the market’s 
[normal]development and
[normal] the
[normal] further expansion of the UK’s district heating networks
[normal],
[normal] as
[normal] 
[normal]outlined
[normal] in the UKDEA’s 
[normal]policy proposals 
[normal] to DECC
[normal] in
[normal] 
[normal]July 2011 and 2012
[normal] (See Appendix
[normal] 2)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] In addition to issues related to public funding, the UKDEA believes that the 
[normal]provision of
[normal] policy ce
[normal]rtainty for investors in low carbon heat generation could also play a crucial role in providing a stable policy framework and a more enabling environment for further investment in low carbon heat networks. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A further hindrance to the
[normal] wider deployment of district heating schemes has been the effect
[normal]s
[normal] of current government policy (coupled with austerity) on local authorities. Local authorities often provide leadership and drive in the establishment of heat networks within their respectiv
[normal]e 
[normal]areas
[normal] and any cuts 
[normal]or 
[normal]reductions to their functions will 
[normal]often result in the shelving or
[normal] abandoning of planned projects including district heating schemes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Another
[normal] equally
[normal] important reason why district heating may not be more common in the UK is the per
[normal]ceived risk involved in making an investment in district heating. D
[normal]evelopers and investors may perceive investing in other technologies as relatively less risky by comparison to investing in district heating projects.
[normal] Again the development of a more mature
[normal] market for district heating can help overcome this barrier.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question: [bold]What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Response:[bold] [bold]A diverse range of technologies can be utilised to generate heat within urban areas
[normal] and many of these can be linked to heat networks.
[normal] These technologies include CHP, biomass 
[normal]boilers, deep geothermal 
[normal]and heat
[normal] pumps
[normal].
[normal] In situations where these technologies re
[normal]place old and polluting plant locally, their use
[normal] result
[normal]s
[normal] in improved
[normal] energy efficiency and a
[normal] subsequent reduction in carbon emissions
[normal] and improvement in air quality
[normal].
[normal] The use of CHP with district heating for instance has led to substantial carbon savings on
[normal] some schemes run by UKDEA members. 
[normal]Figure 1[bold] below shows the
[normal] increasing
[normal] carbon savings made by
[normal] three
[normal] district heating
[normal] schemes
[normal] over a number of years.
[normal] The three schemes- Birmingham, Cofely East London Energy
[normal] (Olympic Park) and Leiceste
[normal]r district heating 
[normal]schemes
[normal] are all operated by UKDEA membe
[normal]rs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Fig 1: [bold]Showing t
[normal]otal CO
[normal]2 
[normal]savings
[normal] made by
[normal] Birmingham, 
[normal]CELE (
[normal]Olympic Park) &amp; Leicester district heating schemes
[normal] from 2008
[normal] to 2012.
[normal]T
[normal]he deployment in urban areas of decentralised energy generating 
[normal]technologies
[normal] can lead to
[normal] a localised
[normal] i
[normal]ncrease in the emission of pollutants such as nitrogen –oxides (NOx) or particulate matter (PM), depending on the generation technology chosen. The use of Best Available Technologies and the efficient operation of tech
[normal]nology should still lead to a reduction in pollutants compared to conventional heat and electricity generation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As 
[normal]many
[normal] of our
[normal] members’
[normal] operation
[normal]s involve partnering 
[normal]local
[normal] authorities in the provision of low carbon heat, the improvement of local air quality standards assumes
[normal] even greater
[normal] importance as it helps our local authority partners meet the requirements of their respective Local Air Quality Management (LAQM) systems 
[normal]and ultimately the legally binding EU air quality standards at national level
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In addition the generation of heat locally through energy from waste schemes within some urban areas has in cases helped alleviate the problem of urban waste disposal whilst s
[normal]imultaneously helping provide low cost heating locally. Over recent years the Coventry Energy from waste plant has led to notable reductions in the volumes of waste destined for landfill through the increased heat recovery from such waste.
[normal] Heat recovery fr
[normal]om this scheme resulted in
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]nitial carbon savings 
[normal]of
[normal] around 2000 tonnes
[normal]. Based on
[normal] the calculations of the
[normal] UKDEA 
[normal]involved with the scheme,
[normal] 
[normal]heat supplied to consumers from this scheme will result in consumers making a 5% financial saving relative to the conv
[normal]entional alternative.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Deep geothermal heat, such as that currently utilised in the Southampton district heating scheme and also planned for Manchester city centre is a renewable resource
[normal] and
[normal] has low spatial requirements thus making it ideally suited to city centre locations where space is at a premium. 
[normal]This helps reduce its local environmental impact.
[normal]&#xa0;
