[normal]Question: [bold]Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy dem[bold]and both diurnally and annually.[bold]&#xa0;[bold] What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Response: [bold]The UKDEA agrees that thermal storage is a potentially useful method of bala
[normal]ncing electricity/energy demand and will t
[normal]herefore welcome any government policy in support of thermal storage.
[normal] 
[normal]Thermal storage will allow energy generated during periods of low heat demand to be stored and later released when households require heat.
[normal]However we are presently unaware of any govern
[normal]ment p
[normal]olicy promoting thermal storage.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question:[bold] 
[normal]Should the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Response:[bold] [bold]As the wider effects of climate change begin to translate into more frequent episodes of very high 
[normal]temperatures over the UK summer period, there is a need for greater focus on the provision of efficient cooling systems
[normal].
[normal] Although the Government has rightly focused on the provision of low cost
[normal] and low carbon
[normal] heating, the UKDEA believes that Government can
[normal] do more with respect to the provision of efficient cooling. The Energy Performance of Buildings Directive makes provision for strategies that enhance the thermal performances of buildings during the summer period (to be given priority) so as to avoid issu
[normal]es such as overheating.
[normal] In addition to increased emphasis on passive cooling techniques, district cooling may provide an efficient means of cooling both old and new building stock.
[normal] Economies of scale mean that large scale district cooling plant can achieve
[normal] substantial carbon and cost savings compared to a proliferation of small scale
[normal] air-conditioning split units in urban areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question: What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity producti[bold]on plus domestic heat pumps?   [bold]&#xa0;[bold]Response:[bold] [bold]The use of electricity
[normal] alone
[normal] in the provision of space heating is not a sensible option. Using ce
[normal]ntralised electricity
[normal] and domestic heat pumps to provide space heating (in place of gas and other energy sources) would result in the
[normal] failure of the electricity grid to 
[normal]cope with the
[normal] resulting
[normal] increased demand placed on it especially during times of high heat demand such as th
[normal]e cold winter period
[normal]s
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fig 2[bold]: Showing a comparison
[normal] of national
[normal] heat and electricity demand variability across a year (domestic and commercial)-2010.
[normal]Source[bold]:
[normal] 
[normal]DECC,
[normal] The Future of Heating: A strategic framework for low carbon heat in the UK
[normal], March 2012
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The use of gas to provide space heating therefore still has signi
[normal]ficant merit as it substantially
[normal] reduces demand on an electricity grid already struggling to cope with existing demand
[normal] as illustrated in Figure 2 above. In addition the e
[normal]fficient use of tech
[normal]nologies such as gas fuelled CHP can still achieve substantial carbon emissions savings 
[normal]compared to conventional
[normal] heat sources.
[normal]The use of electricity alone in the provision of space heating could also lead to an increase in the levels of fuel poverty due t
[normal]o the high and increasing cost of electricity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Low carbon heat generation 
[normal]systems
[normal] such as district heating which
[normal] are largely fuelled by gas can
[normal] therefore play a
[normal]n increasingly
[normal] significant role in helping stabilise and reduce
[normal] demand on the
[normal] electricity gri
[normal]d. 
[normal]As heat networks can be powered by a wide range of fuels such as biomass
[normal] and deep geothermal (in some cases)
[normal] this makes them an even more attractive option for supplying space heating relative to centralised electricity and heat pumps which place a mas
[normal]sive demand on the electricity grid.
[normal] More importantly, due to their fuel agnostic nature heat networks and similar schemes started with gas fired CHP as the principal fuel source can be continually decarbonised 
[normal]through the  greater use of renewable heating
[normal] technologies as they expand and grow.
