[normal]Appendix 2: UKDEA policy proposals for the Department of Energy and Climate Change[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator Fund
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A Policy Proposal for:
[normal]The Department of Energy and Climate Change
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]July 2011
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]The UK Government has demonstrated a desire for increased deployment of district energy, which is proven to be an effective way to provide wide areas and diverse c
[normal]ustomer bases with low carbon energy supplies.  The UK’s current exploitation of district energy is very low compared to our continental neighbours.  However many of the UK’s district energy schemes which are already in operation have clearly demonstrated 
[normal]the substantial benefits that stand to be realise, from reduction of fuel poverty through to greenhouse gas emission savings far in excess of those which can be achieved with the efforts of individual consumers.
[normal]District energy networks typically require a
[normal] small number of core loads to get started and then expand in a relatively organic process, picking up consumers within near reach.  In this way, it can take many years for even a modest number of new consumers to connect to any given district energy schem
[normal]e.  Servicing wider areas with district energy networks before potential consumers are contracted to connect is simply not possible, due to the small operational margins of the Energy Service Companies (ESCOs) which operate district energy schemes.
[normal]The pro
[normal]posed Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator Fund (LCIAF) would operate as a loan fund, enabling pre-servicing of high heat density areas with district energy infrastructure.  This would enable new consumers to be added to district energy networks at a subs
[normal]tantially increased rate, helping to decarbonise whole areas of towns and cities.  Repayments towards the loan would be made whenever new consumers connect to the pre-serviced sections of network.  This form of fund is potentially more sustainable than gra
[normal]nt funding, as re-payments are re-cycled back into the fund to help incentivise further district energy network installation, maximising the benefits achieved for the given expenditure.
[normal]In addition to accelerating the deployment of low carbon energy across
[normal] the UK, the LCIAF would bring in increased investment from ESCOs, not just towards district energy infrastructure but also for the low carbon energy plant needed to provide these new consumers with energy.
[normal]Sections 1 to 3 of this paper provide more detail
[normal]ed background to the current situation and Section 4 proposes a method for the LCIAF to rapidly increase the deployment of low carbon district energy projects throughout the UK.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK’s District Energy Industry[bold]The UK Government’s intentions for increase
[normal]d deployment of District Energy seem clear.  In a recent speech to the Royal Geographical Society
[normal], Chris Huhne called for “more district heating schemes” to help reduce wasted energy.  Greg Barker suggested in a speech to the European Energy Forum in Octo
[normal]ber
[normal], that the Green Investment Bank could be used to invest in district heating.  DECC’s own Community Energy Online Portal contains links to a significant volume of information on District Heating.  
[normal]However, all of this positivity has to be seen in the 
[normal]context of a significantly under-developed district energy sector in the UK.
[normal]Current Take-up of District Heating in the United Kingdom[bold]P
[normal]ö
[normal]yry’s
[normal] Report to the Department of Energy and Climate Change in April 2009 estimated that district heating “currently provides less than 2% of UK heat demand”
[normal].  In contrast, use of district heating in continental Europe is far more widespread; the same report i
[normal]dentifies that Austria, Finland and Denmark benefit from 18%, 49% and 60% of their total heat supplies, respectively, coming from district heating.
[normal]UK District Energy Association Schemes[bold]Members of the UK District Energy Association have already proved tha
[normal]t district energy can play a successful role in mitigating the UK’s greenhouse gas emissions.  District energy schemes operated by UKDEA members deliver over 500 million kWh of heat every year
[normal], saving approximately 100,000 tonnes of carbon emissions per a
[normal]nnum when compared to conventional alternative forms of heat supply.
[normal]Beyond the significant carbon emission savings achieved by UKDEA members’ schemes, fuel poverty and constraints on business competitiveness are tackled too.  For example: 
[normal]The UK’s Potential[bold]The figures clearly demonstrate that the UK’s district energy potential is not yet being fulfilled.  UK heat sales (including industrial heat use) total 15.7 million MWh
[normal].  In Germany, sales of heat just from
[normal] district heating schemes (i.e. 
[normal]not
[normal] including industrial heat use) are approximately 74.2 million MWh
[normal]; over four and a half times the UK’s 
[normal]total
[normal] heat sales.
[normal]Pöyry’s report demonstrated that the carbon savings achieved by district heating are, on average, 
[normal]much greater than achieved by stand-alone renewable technologies
[normal].  With heat responsible for almost half of the UK’s carbon emissions
[normal], there is no doubt that an increase in delivery of district energy would result in substantial reductions in the UK’s ca
[normal]rbon emissions.  
[normal]As stated on the “distributed energy and heat” section of DECC’s website, “a radical shift is needed in how electricity and heat is generated, delivered and used in homes and businesses”
[normal].
[normal]Previous Support for District Energy[bold]A number of 
[normal]funding schemes have previously been available in the UK to support the development of district energy.  However, whilst the first two funding schemes detailed below have resulted in the development and expansion of district energy in the UK, none of these
[normal] funding mechanisms are available today.
[normal]Community Energy [bold]Programme[bold]Historically, this support and grant funding programme has been the most significant funding stream for supporting district energy projects.  The Community Energy Programme (CEP) provided 
[normal]grant capital for installing district heating networks.  This scheme was withdrawn in 2006.
[normal]Low Carbon Infrastructure Fund[bold]This initiative was delivered by a partnership of DECC, the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG) and the Homes and 
[normal]Communities Agency (HCA).  This grant funding stream for low carbon community heating schemes is now finished, with all funding committed and no further funding available at present.
[normal]Regional Infrastructure Funding[bold]Regional Development Agencies (RDAs) 
[normal]offered this as a potential funding model, whereby European funds were used as loan funding to extend the reach of district energy networks, allowing speculative development of energy networks which could attract consumers at greater rates than the typical
[normal] “organic growth” model of district heating.  Repayments of the loan funding were expected to be made each time a new consumer connected to the district 
[normal]energy network.
[normal]  A UKDEA member explored this potential in considerable detail prior to the recent chan
[normal]ges to the Regional Development Agencies.
[normal]Limitations of the Current Support Regime[bold]Despite DECC’s recognition of the need for a “radical shift” in how energy is delivered, support for district energy is now piecemeal and often short-term.  Mechanisms such
[normal] as Enhanced Capital Allowances, CCL Exemption, Renewable Obligation Certificates and the Renewable Heat Incentive, all help to incentivise various forms of low carbon technology.  However, none of these mechanisms incentivise the district energy networks 
[normal]that could accelerate the deployment of low carbon energy to multiple consumers on an effective, decentralised basis, rather than relying on piecemeal action by individual consumers.
[normal]District energy schemes expand through a relatively organic process, conn
[normal]ecting new developments (and existing buildings at the end of plant-replacement cycles) that are within reach of the existing network.  Costs of new connections can be high, primarily because of the expensive civil works and specialist pipe materials invol
[normal]ved.  These connections are typically funded by a “capital connection charge”, intended to be no more expensive than the alternative costs of a conventional energy plant solution, so as to incentivise connection.  
[normal]Operators of district energy schemes are 
[normal]unable to fund speculative pre-servicing of areas themselves, because operational margins are simply not sufficient.  If wider delivery of district energy is to be achieved, a means must be established to accelerate the reach of existing schemes and furthe
[normal]r incentivise the commissioning of new ‘core schemes’ with the possibility of rapid expansion to new consumers.
[normal]DECC have clearly placed significant emphasis on the drive for community energy.  Without adequate financial support however, community action w
[normal]ill be stifled and opportunities will be missed.  The long term nature of energy supply and plant replacement cycles means that once a chance of connection to a low carbon energy supply is missed, the opportunity can be wasted for decades to come.  Relying
[normal] on sporadic grant funding schemes results in ‘feast and famine’ delivery, rather than the necessary sustainable growth of district energy networks which can capture opportunities as they arise.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator Fund[bold]This proposed
[normal] ‘Low Carbon Infrastructure Accelerator Fund’ is based in part around the ‘Regional Infrastructure Fund’ mechanism once put forward by Regional Development Agencies.
[normal]Awards from the proposed loan fund would enable district energy schemes to pre-service are
[normal]as of high heat density.  Pre-agreed re-payments of the loan are made when new energy consumers connect to these district energy networks, and the re-payments are funded by those consumers’ connection charges.  More effective than grants, this funding mech
[normal]anism can be more self-sustaining, recycling the revenues to new schemes and maximising the delivery of low-carbon energy schemes nationwide. 
[normal]This method of funding would also bring increased investment from ESCOs into both district energy networks and al
[normal]so the low carbon plant required to provide the substantially increased customer base with energy.  As an example of where increased private sector funding would be brought in by the LCIAF, an ESCO would be able to fund and develop an energy centre on the 
[normal]basis of revenues received from a consumer connecting to the far end of an LCIAF pre-funded network; such a building would not have been able to take part in a district energy scheme in the absence of the LCIAF funded network and the district energy scheme
[normal] would have been smaller or even unviable as a result.  
[normal]Figure 
[normal]1
[normal] below illustrates this effect; for this hypothetical development area, the solid red line represents the district energy network that would normally be economically feasible, only supplying the nearest section of development.  The development zone to the 
[normal]right of the figure is therefore unable to benefit from low carbon and low cost energy supplies from the district energy scheme and the scheme may be less efficient with the smaller total energy loads.  The dotted red line illustrates a section of LCIAF fu
[normal]nded network, picking up all initial phases of development as well as pre-servicing an area for later development phases, thereby maximising take-up of the low carbon district energy solution and allowing an ESCO to invest in developing the most effective 
[normal]solution for these larger energy loads.
[normal]Figure 
[normal]1
[normal] - Example of LCIAF extending the reach and effectiveness of a district energy solution
[normal]A number of case studies exist which demonstrate both the success of similar funding mechanis
[normal]ms and where substantial opportunities for development of low carbon energy have been missed, due to lack of available support.  The UKDEA is able to work with DECC in developing policy on a robust evidence-base.
[normal]It’s important to note that additional bene
[normal]fits arise from the future-proofing nature of district energy networks; district energy solutions allow even lower-carbon forms of energy generation to be installed in later years, as they become viable, continuing to decarbonise every customer in the year
[normal]s to come without the need for substantial further effort and investment by those consumers.
[normal]Proposed Mechanism[bold]A more detailed overview of the proposed mechanism is set out below:
[normal]Recycling of Funding[bold]Repayments into the fund from consumer connection charges can be recycled out to further low carbon infrastructure projects, making the LCIAF an
[normal] ‘ever-greening’ and more sustainable form of support.  A target long-stop date for the LCIAF could allow further returns 
[normal]to the fund to be put towards other areas, once delivery of low carbon infrastructure has been sufficiently accelerated.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 
[normal]2
[normal] – Example Early Years Delivery of LCIAF
[normal]Figure 
[normal]3
[normal] - Illustration of the Low Carbon Infrastructure Fund Mechanism
[normal]Sources of Funding &amp; Projected Benefits[bold]As set out in 
[normal]Figure 
[normal]3
[normal], there are a number of potential sources of funding to support the LCIAF, including the ERDF, General Taxation, JESSCIA funding and payments made as part of zero carbon ‘allowable solutions’.
[normal]The Scottish Government have recently announced a district heating loan fund which should not only incentivise action nationwide but could also provide a useful foundation from which policy makers can proceed and lessons can be learnt
[normal].
[normal]Based on previous 
[normal]levels of funding for district energy, the UKDEA estimate that £50 million pounds is an adequate fund size to incentivise very significant delivery and expansion of district energy, across more than fifty separate areas.  This fund could be fully recovered
[normal] over the long-term, and has the potential to offset in excess of 6 million tonnes of CO
[normal]2
[normal] emissions over the new district energy infrastructure’s lifetime.  Members of the UKDEA are willing to undertake detailed analysis and provide supporting evidence to 
[normal]DECC, should this proposal be of interest, to enable a realistic evidence-base to form the basis of policy.  
