[normal]References[bold]Addendum 1 – Projected Employment Figures[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]The Government has made clear that it plans to increase deployment of district energy in 
[normal]the UK.  This laudable and necessary aspiration needs to be seen in the context of a significantly under-developed district energy sector, compared to its technical potential and the development of district energy in other European Countries where specific
[normal] support mechanisms have been utilised to encourage growth/support networks.
[normal]One of the central aims of the UK District Energy Association is to engage with Government and share the experience of its members, to accelerate the deployment of low-carbon dist
[normal]rict energy across the UK.
[normal]The UKDEA is not a trade organisation but instead counts as its Full Members, bodies that are responsible for developing and operating most of the successful district energy schemes in the UK.  Our members include not just privat
[normal]e sector energy service companies (ESCOs) but also the public sector authorities who are centrally involved in the development of district energy schemes.
[normal]Current take up of district energy in the UK is estimated to be less than 2% of heat demand.  In adva
[normal]nce of the published results of DECC’s district heating survey, we have undertaken analysis which demonstrates that it should be feasible to supply over 100 TWh of heat (14% of the UK’s heating and hot water demands) through low-carbon district heating net
[normal]works.
[normal]Assuming total decarbonisation of these networks in the run-up to 2050, the greenhouse gas emissions savings should exceed over 36 MtCO
[normal]2
[normal]e – a 26% reduction in the current greenhouse gas emissions relating to heating and hot water.
[normal]The current energy
[normal] and legislative landscape contains a number of barriers which prevent deployment of district energy, including shortfalls in potential support mechanisms.  District energy often provides the most cost effective means of decarbonising energy supplies on a 
[normal]whole-life cost basis but does suffer from high capital costs.  We have included a basic summary table in this paper of typical district heating costs.  Additionally, we are happy to work with DECC to help develop a more detailed evidence base.
[normal]In Section 
[normal]3, we have proposed a number of distinct policy measures to accelerate the delivery of low-carbon district energy schemes to achieve the realistic but challenging target of delivering within the next 20 years 14% of all heat in the UK from low carbon distr
[normal]ict energy schemes.  These are summarised below:
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A low carbon heat network incentive of 0.75p/kWh – providing a 
[normal]long-term revenue stream for low carbon heat sales through district energy networks, just as with the RHI.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Lastly, we have provided two worked examples in Section 4, based on feasibility 
[normal]studies for actual district energy schemes, and how the measures proposed could help to remove the barriers to their delivery.  The case studies demonstrate that these specific policy measures 
[normal]will
[normal] unlock the potential for the rapid expansion of district e
[normal]nergy in the UK, as set out in this paper.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK’s District Energy Industry[bold]The UK Government has clear declared intentions for increased deployment of District Energy.  However, this positivity has to be seen in the context of a significantly under-deve
[normal]loped district energy sector in the UK.
[normal]Current Take-up of District Heating in the United Kingdom[bold]P
[normal]ö
[normal]yry’s
[normal] Report to the Department of Energy and Climate Change in April 2009 estimated that district heating “currently provides less than 2% of UK heat demand”
[normal].  In contrast, use of district heating in continental Europe is far more widespread; the same report i
[normal]dentifies that Austria, Finland and Denmark benefit from 18%, 49% and 60% of their total heat supplies, respectively, coming from district heating.  
[normal]DECC is now putting substantial effort into understanding the true extent of the UK’s existing district en
[normal]ergy schemes, engaging BRE and Databuild to undertake a detailed, nationwide assessment of district energy.  The results of this survey will be a national database which can form a detailed evidence base around which to form future policy. The UKDEA and it
[normal]s members have been playing an active role in the development of this national assessment which it had identified was an essential requirement to build the “knowledge base for district energy in the UK”, from which the desired growth can be planned.
[normal]UK Dis[bold]trict Energy Association[bold] Schemes[bold]Members of the UK District Energy Association have already proved that district energy can play a successful role in mitigating the UK’s greenhouse gas emissions.  District energy schemes operated by UKDEA members deliver o
[normal]ver 600 million kWh of heat every year
[normal], saving approximately 100,000 tonnes of carbon emissions per annum when compared to conventional alternative forms of heat supply.
[normal]Figure 
[normal]4
[normal] - Breakdown of the low carbon heat sources for UKDEA schemes
[normal]Beyond the significant carbon emission savings achieved by UKDEA members’ schemes, fuel poverty and constraints on business competitiveness are tackled too.  For example: 
[normal]The UK’s Potential[bold]Whilst successful schemes exist in the UK, the figures clearly demonstrate that the UK’s vast district energy potential is not yet being fulfilled.  UK heat sales (including industrial heat use) total 15.7 million
[normal] MWh
[normal].  By comparison, in Germany, sales of heat just from district heating schemes (i.e. 
[normal]not
[normal] including industrial heat use) are approximately 74.2 million MWh
[normal]; over four and a half times the UK’s 
[normal]total
[normal] heat sales.
[normal]Pöyry’s report demonstrated that the car
[normal]bon savings achieved by district heating are, on average, much greater than achieved by stand-alone renewable technologies
[normal].  With heat responsible for approximately half of the UK’s total carbon emissions
[normal], there is no doubt that an increase in delivery o
[normal]f district energy schemes would result in substantial reductions in the UK’s carbon emissions.  
[normal]As stated on the “distributed energy and heat” section of DECC’s website, “a radical shift is needed in how electricity and heat is generated, delivered and us
[normal]ed in homes and businesses”
[normal].
[normal]It is essential to quantify the opportunities for development of district energy, prior to and notwithstanding the completion of Databuild and BRE’s detailed UK district energy survey of existing schemes.  We have therefore un
[normal]dertaken some detailed analysis of the potential for new district energy schemes across the UK based on our members extensive knowledge of what can realistically be delivered in any urban area.
[normal]The Analysis[bold]District energy schemes are most effective (in te
[normal]rms of cost-effectiveness, energy efficiency and carbon savings) in highly heat dense areas, where substantial heat demands can be met with a minimum of installed network.
[normal]The analysis did not seek to provide a comprehensive look at the total potential for
[normal] district energy but instead concentrated on the largest 200 (by population) UK towns &amp; cities.  Many of these cities already have some form of district energy networks in place, from small networks based around individual developments or housing estates t
[normal]o large city scale schemes.  We have included details of existing UKDEA member schemes in the analysis, where possible, to base our calculations on a practical real world evidence base.  The analysis therefore gives an indication of the 
[normal]increase
[normal] in heat su
[normal]pplied through large scale urban district energy, which could be achieved over the coming years in the appropriate legislative landscape.
[normal]Notwithstanding the importance of this potential, there is additionally substantial potential to decarbonise the natio
[normal]n’s heat supplies through many smaller scale communal and district heating schemes based around smaller clusters of heat dense consumers, such as new mixed use developments and rural estates.
[normal]The time required to deliver the projected schemes will vary sub
[normal]stantially from case to case.  Many Local Authorities have already investigated the potential for district energy within their 
[normal]boundaries but are unsure how to proceed with delivery.  Many potential schemes face specific barriers to their delivery and many
[normal] Local Authorities will not currently hold any assessments of the potential for district energy within their boundaries.  Realising the potential will be heavily reliant on an improved legislative landscape for district energy, without which the necessary 
[normal]scale of deployment cannot be realised.
[normal]All settlements where schemes were not already in place were assumed to start with a core scheme selling circa 10,000 MWh heat per annum.  This figure was estimated as an average of core scheme sizes in a set of rece
[normal]nt feasibility studies undertaken by one UKDEA member.  The schemes can then grow by connecting new consumers.  The rate at which this growth occurs, and the size that is reached by each district energy scheme, depends on the size of each settlement.  Bein
[normal]g one of the most easily accessible data sets, this analysis was based on the populations of the towns and cities in question
[normal].  It was assumed that district energy schemes initially follow a similar level of delivered heat per population as current good p
[normal]ractice UK district heating schemes operated by UKDEA members. 
[normal]Furthermore, towards 2030, it’s assumed that district energy schemes should grow in scale to match well developed European schemes on a kWh/population basis, such as the district heating schem
[normal]e in Vienna, Austria.
[normal]Assuming current barriers to district energy can be effectively reduced, disincentives removed and appropriate incentives put in place (as set out in this paper), the initial installation of core district energy schemes, for every one
[normal] of the 200 towns and cities analysed, could take between 2 years and 5 years
[normal].  Once this has been achieved, substantial growth can take place, with significant increases in connected consumers over the following decades.
[normal]The detailed analysis can be 
[normal]viewed in Appendix 1 to this paper.  The results are certainly not an upper limit on the potential for district energy in the UK as they concentrate on larger scale schemes and may well underestimate the potentially important role of smaller scale district
[normal] energy.
[normal]By 2030, it could be possible to supply over 100 TWh p.a. of heat through district energy networks, which is over 14% of the UK’s current heating and hot water demands.  Assuming these district energy schemes provide heat with similar carbon savin
[normal]gs (when compared to heat from a mixture of boiler plant and grid electricity) to existing good practice energy from waste and CHP based systems, the greenhouse gas emissions averted would be in excess of 28 MtCO
[normal]2
[normal]e.  If all these district energy systems th
[normal]en fully decarbonise, the averted annual GHG emissions top 36 MtCO
[normal]2
[normal]e – 26% of the nation’s current greenhouse gas emissions related to supply of heating and hot water.
[normal]Figure 
[normal]5
[normal] - Potential Growth of Low Carbon District Energy in the UK.
[normal]Making it Happen[bold]Despite DECC’s recognition of the need for a “radical shift” in how energy is delivered, support for district energy is now piecemeal and often short-term.  Mechanisms such as En
[normal]hanced Capital Allowances, CCL Exemption, Renewable Obligation Certificates and the Renewable Heat Incentive, all help to incentivise various forms of low carbon technology.  However, none of these mechanisms have been implemented with regard to the distri
[normal]ct energy networks that could accelerate the deployment of low carbon energy to multiple consumers on an effective, decentralised basis, rather than relying on piecemeal action by individual consumers.
[normal]Costs of installing district energy network can be hig
[normal]h, primarily because of the expensive civil works and specialist pipe materials involved.  We have set out below some current typical network installation costs, to help improve DECC’s current evidence base.
[normal]All costs averaged to give typical figures per m
[normal]etre trench length.
